TY  - JOUR
T1  - Breaking the Bonds of Reciprocity in Negotiations
AU  - Brett, Jeanne M.
AU  - Shapiro, Debra L.
AU  - Lytle, Anne L.
Y1  - 1998/08/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/257081
DO  - 10.5465/257081
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 410
EP  - 424
VL  - 41
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We tested hypotheses concerning the effectiveness of three strategies for breaking conflict spirals in negotiations. We also investigated the relationship between outcomes and the relative frequency of reciprocated contentious communications. Results confirmed the hypotheses, showing that extreme distributive outcomes are related to the relative frequency of reciprocated contentious communications and that conflict spirals can be stopped by various communication strategies. Theoretical and practical implications for managing contentious negotiations are discussed.
AB  - We tested hypotheses concerning the effectiveness of three strategies for breaking conflict spirals in negotiations. We also investigated the relationship between outcomes and the relative frequency of reciprocated contentious communications. Results confirmed the hypotheses, showing that extreme distributive outcomes are related to the relative frequency of reciprocated contentious communications and that conflict spirals can be stopped by various communication strategies. Theoretical and practical implications for managing contentious negotiations are discussed.
